< text>
Well laid out Planet Fitness location. Everything you expect from this chain of gyms. Equipment in very good shape and plenty of it. Plenty of free weights, Smith machines and benches. Friendly, upbeat staff. Beverages available for purchase.

Plenty of free parking. It is a large lot. Grocery store, restaurants and a variety of other stores in this shopping complex.

Nice area.< /text>

<review>I would consider this a good gym, but nothing fantastic. I'm not a fan of gyms or working out in front of other people in general, but this place gets the job done, and you can't beat the $10 per month fee. They have a lot of cardio equipment, which is most of the reason why I go there. I generally only go during the low time of the day, between 1:00pm to 3:00pm to avoid the crowds. I've been at night, and you basically spend more time bumping elbows with strangers and waiting for equipment to open up than actually working out. I get very irritated by the number of people who aren't serious about working out. There's always people babysitting the machines; just sitting there on their phones and not lifting a single muscle, or people who think the gym is a social place. I really wish the staff would be more attentive to that and say something to the lazy people. I suppose that's just the sort of people these less expensive gyms attract. I'm also a little disappointed that there aren't any real classes. You can sign up for small group lessons where you focus on a certain body part, but I already know how to do that, or I could watch a YouTube video for ideas. If I could afford a gym that teaches yoga, self-defense, or a sport, I'd go there instead. Still, if you're just looking for an inexpensive place to lift weights and do some cardio, then Planet Fitness is your place.</review>< Pics>
None< /Pics>

<UserId.>111247715558032159574<//UserId.><username>Mini Virmani</username>< time>

< Rating>
4< /Rating>
< text>
I had a great experience living at Solamonte for 2 years. The management and maintenance both are great. The BEST thing was that they were really great and considerate when I was moving in and moving out. My apartment wasn't ready on the date of move-in but my movers had arrived with my stuff and Solamonte made arrangement for move-in on the same day. Upon move out, there were few charges that I disagreed with and discussed with them and they happily removed from the bill. Very responsive people especially Adam. He would always smile while giving you your packages (They later installed electronic package system which is cool. You'd get email or text msg and could retrieve packages on your own!). The ONLY CONCERN I had was that during renovation, the clubhouse was closed for a long time and the rent wasn't adjusted accordingly. They allowed the residents to use amenities at their other properties which was good but overall such long renovation was little inconvenient. Regardless, the people, management, maintenance, location, quality of life there, everything was wonderful. They communicate really well and you'll often have flyers on your doors to share information with you. My apartment was spacious, neighbors were awesome, and I would definitely recommend this property to anyone. Short drive from Ontario Airport as well. Don't forget to check out many beautiful parks nearby!< /text>

<user_id>103770324981974714040</user_id><Name>Christine</Name><Date>1533852903338<//Date>< rating>
5</rating>
< Text>
TLDR Version: Apartments are great, staff is friendly, quick maintenance response, dog friendly.  Love living here.

I've lived at Solamonte for almost 5 months now and have no major complaints. We were warned that they would be going under a major remodel before we moved in so we haven't been able to use any amenities yet.

Pros:
- Excellent Staff: Friendly, Answer e-mails generally within 24 hours, or I can walk in during business hours to the leasing office.
- Quiet Area: Neighbors are usually pretty quiet. Kids do run around on occasion.
-Maintenance Requests are easy to submit and responded to quickly: You can submit a request online easily and is fixed within a day or two.
-Animal friendly: I had a hard time finding a place that would allow me to have my Husky and Solamonte doesn't restrict Huskies.
-W/D Hookup IN Unit: Speaks for itself.
-Nice area: Nice backdrop of mountain when going for walks or you can get an apartment with a view ( additional cost to rent ).
-Valet trash pickup: Just put trash outside your door at designated times and someone picks it up ( added to rent costs ).
-Security Patrol: Patrol at night and it's a gated community, although the gate is easy to get through if you follow someone in.

Cons:
Construction: Was quoted for a 2 months time table period and we're on month 3. Been here almost 5 months without having been able to use amenities.
Package pickup: Any mail delivered goes to leasing office so you have to make it to the leasing office before they close to get packages delivered BUT the remodel is supposed to provide us with our own package holding boxes so we won't have to do this anymore.
Dog Poop: A lot of pet owners are lazy and don't pick up their dogs poop, the staff have sent out e-mails and letters about it to try and help promote poo pickup. At least there are sprinklers everywhere to help with clearing up dog pee.
Price: Is a little steep but better than most places I compared.<//Text>

<user_name>emmaline deBecker</user_name>< Resp>

< UserId.>
104177384421182571395</UserId.>
< rating>
2</rating>
<Review>I have eaten here before and the food was decent, not the best Indian food I have had but by far not the worst. Decent prices and portion sizes. However this time around, my experience was much worse. The food was scheduled for pick up at 1:00pm, and the restaurant did not confirm my order until 2:15pm. I understand that they were busy, but I did not know whether or not my order was received. When I went to pick the order up, the employee said that my order was canceled by Door Dash (it was not), even though I had received a message from Door Dash that the order was ready for pick up. After leaving without my order, and after a pretty rude encounter with the worker, I contacted Door Dash to ask why the order was canceled, upon which they said it was not. Ultimately, I did not get a refund from the restaurant, and was on the phone with Door Dash for 45 minutes trying to resolve the issue. My order was finally refunded, and it was determined that Naan Stop had canceled my order without telling me. Overall a very bad customer service experience, and will not be returning.< /Review>< Pictures>

< review>
I used to love this place. Recently they changed their prices so that, instead of getting a better deal on larger orders, large to go containers cost disproportionately more than their smaller counterparts.

8oz Chicken is 5.75
12oz Chicken is 9.75
The difference in volume is 150%
The difference in price is 170%
Then they charge an extra dollar if you want Chicken Tikka Masala!

They clearly changed their pricing to a more predatory model to take advantage of drunk college students. This is a sad cash grab from a great restaurant. I cannot recommend this place anymore. If you want to get a delicious Indian feast, go to Masala Spice.</review>

<resp>None<//resp><Time>1551077768808<//Time><Text>Think Panda Express, but for Indian food.  They have trays of pre-made food and serve straight from them.   It's not gourmet, but I think it tastes pretty good, and it's not absurdly expensive!   I like the chicken tikka masala, but the veggie options are good, too!  If you don't mind paying an extra couple dollars, I'd recommend also getting either a samosa or warm naan.

A word of caution.  There are several menus in the store, so it's a little confusing to order.  I (and the people working there) recommend you just pick something from the blackboard next to the food trays.  I always just get a rice bowl.  Simple and cheaper than most other options!

Something I don't like about this place is the use of plastic and styrofoam bowls and utensils.  Something to keep in mind if you're bothered by using disposable things.</Text><rating>4<//rating>< Gmap_id>

<Review>A fast food version of the standard Indian lunch buffets, you can order complicated meals, or more commonly you can grab a 1 item bowl or 2 item plate. All the standards are here, Chicken Tikka Masala, Vegetable Korma, Chicken Vindaloo, Chana Masala, Saag Paneer, etc. They do variaties of naan that are good and fresh, and the owner who frequently works the register is very nice.
You can eat in, they have a sauce stand for the mint chutney, etc you may want, and some cramped seating for those stopping in for a quick lunch. There's a small shared parking lot as well, making it convenient for lunch even if you have to drive in from outside Isla Vista. Alternatively they do take out, providing separate sauce and rice containers to make it easier to transport, and have both GrubHub and DoorDash.
The prices are very good, it's slightly on the less expensive side for a lunch in the IV area.< /Review><Resp>None</Resp><user_id>109605449616617302353<//user_id><pics>None<//pics>< Rating>

<user_id>109881796759118870608<//user_id><name>social3ngin33rin< /name><Date>1474585405115<//Date>< rating>
4< /rating>
< review>
When you walk in, stay to the right; this is where you will find the menu on the wall and order.  I see people walking up to the register and trying to order, the setup isn't 100% intuitive but that's fine. To be honest, I did the same thing, but I figured it out while waiting for the register guy to ring someone else up. The customer service was good. I chatted briefly with the dude at the register. The two people running the front seemed nice.

I ordered food from here a few days ago. It was amazing. It reminded me of another Indian food place in Los Angeles. Imo the place is a two $$, but for this area it's a single $. After being deprived of food for so long, this really filled me up nicely.

The Earl Grey boba is not worth getting though; it's a real shame because Earl Grey done right can be a really outstanding choice for milk tea boba. The boba was cooked correctly, it wasn't raw nor was it overly soft and falling apart in the straw.

The biggest bonus I would give this place is that they have a cute girl working there ^_^ (They would get 4 stars regardless of her being there or not)< /review>

<date>1583015213768</date><rating>5</rating>< Review>
Always an excellent neighborhood gem!  Mistura serves excellent food without pretentiousness... very straight forward and very very yummy!  Their signature roasted chicken is out of this world, but lately I discovered their Aji Gallina, which is like a Peruvian curry... it's awesome!  I recommend to add the vegetables to any dish you get and for starters, the fried yucca!  The owners are usually at the location... introduce yourselves!  They are very friendly and love to hear from their customers.< /Review>

< Review>
We came on a Monday afternoon right before they close at 2:30 and I walked and made sure it was fine for us to still come in and have lunch.

The hostess/waitress was very friendly and welcoming that she told us "sure come'on in".

We knew what we wanted and placed our orders. The food arrived within 15 minutes and was very delicious.

Irena kept checking on us for redills on beverages and if we needed anything else.

This will be our to go spot.</Review>

<user>110470605488690473816<//user><user_name>Michael Gamarra</user_name><time>1541624523266< /time><Rating>4<//Rating>< Review>
‚Ä¢The "Lomo Saltado" was delicious!! One of the best Lomo Saltados I have tried in Peruvian restaurants within the Bay Area. If you would like to pair it with a red wine, I extremely suggest you to order a glass of "Sunce Zinfandel" or "Sunce Syrah" red wine from the Menu.

‚Ä¢The "Rotisserie Chicken" was okay, that's my opinion as a Peruvian who has lived its entire life in Peru, but I can't say that it was bad. You are going to like it whether you are Peruvian or not. If you are Peruvian, don't expect the "Rotisserie Chicken" to taste or be like a true "Pollo a la Brasa" from Peru.</Review>

Exquisite delicious Peruvian food. Nice ambience and friendly staff. Good quality food (organic and no gmos) for the price. Make sure to try the ceviche and seco de cordero for authentic Peruvian dishes. Of course the rotisserie chicken and sides are finger licking good. <Resp>None<//Resp><gmap_id>0x80c259addcb934a1:0xa1aa3e1d128389a5</gmap_id><Pictures>None</Pictures>< review>
Horrible lady running this place!- I went here because they are the only known salon for SNS nails in this area. I have had SNS nails done in Glendora CA many times and love them, so I came in today for a set but the lady has no clue what she is doing! She had to put 5 coats on my nails and tried to say the powder color I picked is bad but it's just her. When you do SNS nails you are supposed to turn down the speed of the dremel to file it so it doesn't heat the powder back up causing discoloration but she left her dremel on high like you would for a Acrylic nails and just kept trying to blame the color! I had SNS powder and gel top coat all over my finger tips and spent my afternoon picking it off my fingers and cuticles --OMG and they don't have nail clips nor did she even know what nail clips are! Their price list is not straight forward- a "regular set" is $35 but apparently that is just for clear powder and paint over the top- for an actual color it's $40 but she said she would take $5 off for the hassle and then still tried to charge me the full price at the end- I gave her her $35 to pay for product because I am not looking for a free nail job but I will NEVER COME BACK- I would rather take the trip out to Glendora to not deal with this lady again. No one should leave a nail salon having to still clean up their nails - you should walk out feeling like you are ready for any event not having to go home and clean up from their mess. If you are not going to take the time and effort to really learn a new style of nails then DONT OFFER IT! Stick to what you know- I'm sure she does great acrylics as I saw a few ladies with them that looked good but don't come here expecting a good SNS set- she refused to believe me that it was the filing process causing the discoloration and just kept putting more coats of powder on top to then file and ruin. I didnt come for an argument- I came for a nice nail date with my daughter but they put my 7year old at the opposite end of the salon getting her nails painted and then tried to tell her no and giggled at her when she asked for a little heart on each of her nails- I told them to do it as I was paying for her nails and had no problem paying for each heart which they charged $10 for. They should not be telling her "NO" or laughing at a little girls request, they should say "ok let me ask your mom if that is ok" instead of making her feel as though she has done something wrong with a simple request- I have never experienced such terrible attitudes and I understand they were busy but I made an appointment a week in advance so that is not an issue I should have to deal with- if you are busy you have to tell customers to make an appointment- don't rush through and do a bad job just to rush to the next customer- that's how you get a bad reputation and no one wants to come back! Take appointments seriously and create more repeat customers! - sorry end of rant<//review>

<rating>5< /rating>< text>
I am completely new to yoga, so new that my yoga journey started with Honey yoga opening their doors a few months back. This studio and its owners Bridgette and Olivia are absolutely wonderful and delightful. They are so warm and Inviting and I truly feel as if I‚Äôm part of a family. Also they always remember my name and greet my when I walk through the door! (Talk about accountability!)
The practices are well rounded, definitely a perfect fit for newbies like myself or those who can stand on one hand and can bend themselves into cute little pretzels.  I am always supported and encouraged by the instructors and have never felt like I am out of my league with the great mix of skill levels in the practices. I actually enjoy having such different skill levels, makes me set goals farther then just being able to touch my toes!
They also offer classes to help focus on different elements of yoga practice which have been great as well. I always leave feeling inspired and loved. I‚Äôm so appreciative of these Honeys and truly love this gem in our neighborhood!</text>

<Text>I signed up for the 6am class with Amanda via the MindBody Android app...5 mins before the class started haha...and bought the new client $30 for 30 package so I can be unlimited this month and try all the classes. Amanda's Honey 60 class was just what the Dr. ordered! I was on the island of Hawaii last week and hiked Waipio Valley's massively steep grade...my hamstrings have hated me ever since...until this morning!

The studio is so cute! They have all the "extras" you'd expect of a boutique yoga studio: Blocks, Blankets, Cushions, Aromatherapy, straps, dim lighting, even lavender scented eye masks and an Aloe Vera plant.

The studio is easy to find, and highly inviting. The website has great personality. And, I love their logo and brand...It's adorable, professional, and relatable.

Amanda's class was so great! She's an incredibly talented instructor. She gently corrected my form (with my permission), where needed, added the right pressure to intensify the stretches, where appropriate, and even closed with a light, relaxing head massage during Shavasana.

I'm looking forward to continuing my practice at Honey Yoga!</Text>< pics>

<Time>1625858837603< /Time><text>My experience with this company was so negative that I felt compelled to write this review so that others can be wary when dealing with this company - especially if they are considering buying a condo in a CMS managed community. I have read reviews from those who own in a CMS managed community - expressing concerns over their investment literally rotting away due to CMS's management. However, renters should also be wary.

I have suffered the unfortunate experience of residing in a CMS managed community. My experience with their representative, Karen Ecoff, has been absolutely detestable and downright repugnant.

The level of customer service and professionalism I have received, as a result of the above mentioned CMS representative, was little to none during my lease. She consistently ignored issues I tried to bring up or always manages to conveniently blame her secretary. In addition to her lack of accountability, she is regularly responds to my concerns with new, frivolous and unrelated complaints against me. With this kind of management, gaslighting, attitude and (lack of) leadership, nothing was ever resolved, or it took a ridiculous amount of time to do so.

For example, we once went without hot water for nearly a month (in December) partly because the CMS representative, Ecoff, did not believe the water was cold. She had the audacity to vehemently insist that the lukewarm water coming out of both my kitchen sink and shower was hot, while the plumbing contractor was right next to us with a temperature gun confirming it was not the 118 degrees required for it to be considered hot. Unfortunately this wasn't an isolated incident - this happened twice with two different contractors. This blatant example of not caring about your residents was extremely frustrating to say the least, as well as an embarrassment (on CMS/Ecoff's part).

In addition, the community itself was always in a constant state of disarray and disorganization. The mailroom was always messy and mail is frequently stacked in a corner. Delivery drivers are unable to enter the complex (because Karen Ecoff was never in the office during normal business hours to open the gate) so they would resort to honking at the gate. The stream was always dirty or broken.

These are just some, out of a very long list of complaints I have against CMS/Ecoff/Management. For the duration of my lease, it seemed as if there was always a new (and often unresolved) issue/conflict. It got so bad that I had to request that Ecoff desist from contact me (the tenant) directly regarding any complaints/issues regarding the unit. I requested that she contact my landlord/unit owner directly regarding any issues.

In addition to not caring about the residents, the CMS representative never seemed to know which people were residents, forgetting that certain residents were residents. Or perhaps she only cared about certain residents and not others. In my time here, I've noticed certain residents are expected to abide by rules while other residents are not.

Overall, instead of creating a community both efficient and welcoming, the CMS Rep seeks to (unsuccessfully) police the community she has been hired to manage. Needless to say, I did not renew my lease and chose a different community - one that values efficiency, communication and excellent customer service; as well as a community where (ALL) residents are valued.

If you would like to read more feedback on CMS, look up their Yelp page. Their ratings are just as low there.<//text>< user>

<review>A lot of fun for really a very reasonable price!

Urban Putt is for sure a SF staple among the 21-29 crowd so I was glad to finally make it over there a couple weekends ago for a little birthday fun.

It‚Äôs only 12 bucks a person to play which was surprising considering the popularity of this place, and we were able to get canned beer for only 3 bucks a pop which blew me away. A very wide selection of craft cocktails and different beers so definitely makes for a fun game of golf (even if your game suffers a little bit).

When we came it was around 5pm on a Saturday and it was crazy crowded - took about 30 minutes to make it to the course and people are either waiting on you or you on them basically most of the time which is tough. I know it‚Äôs 21+ after 8 though so I personally would opt for that in the future.

Courses are very unique and fun - I was surprised by their originality. It‚Äôs not a full 18 holes, just 14 but that actually feels like a good number by the time you get there.

Tons of fun would definitely go back!<//review>< Pics>

<name>Ben Christoforides<//name>< date>
1566371589243< /date>
<rate>5<//rate>< Text>
What an amazing place! We started our evening at the restaurant on the second floor. The food was delicious, service was great, and the drinks were good. The food wasn't too pricey but I do think the drink prices are a bit steep considering how small they are. After dinner, we went downstairs to pay for mini golf. The woman at the register had great customer service and gave my boyfriend a free game since it was his birthday. There was a bit of a line to begin playing, but we got drinks from the bar and observed the other players while we waited. Each course was very unique and exciting. Some were more challenging than others but it was all fun. The place isn't too big so we ended up in a couple traffic jams with other players. You're allowed to bring your drinks on the course and tables are provided at each hole. We went on Wednesday night and it was surprisingly packed. Everyone we met was really nice and we plan to come back!< /Text>

< Review>
We came here for our company outing from 4pm-7pm on Thursday (20 people) and we taken really good care of. We had private room reserved for playing hoops and skee-ball and eat and drink, and we also played a round of minigolf (of course). It is a really cute, fun, well-though out course that wasn't too hard for us non-pro minigolfers.

The drinks were top-notch (had Stairway to Heaven & Gin Lime Ricky), food pretty good (only 2 vegan options though, the mini vegan tacos and a green salad), but the boys had plenty of sliders and pizza to keep them satisfied . Service was excellent starting from the bartender and ending to the manager who kept making sure we were allright with drinks and food and the space and he even offered us to keep the room as late as we wanted since it was a slow night which was magnificent bonus for the youngsters who can still stay up later than 7pm. I'd def recommend this place for company outings as well as a date night.</Review>

<Rate>2< /Rate>< Review>
A fun idea, very badly designed and managed. Expect long waiting times, followed by bottleneck after bottleneck. The 4th hole, a sort of video game, had a line backed up through the entire play area. Other holes featured mechanical gimmicks that took far too long to play out and, multiple times during our visit, jammed up.

This might be worth trying on a slow night after 8pm when it's 21-and-up. If people are waiting outside, just keep walking.< /Review>

< Text>
This is hands down one of my favorite putt putt spots.

Urban Putt is a putt putt golf place located in the Mission district of San Francisco. It's a relatively cramped place that makes the most use out of its space. It's a San Francisco themed course were creative and original. I've never seen any other putt putt places use as many ideas as this place.

You'll spend about 1-2 hours here assuming that the line moves rather quickly. ~$10 per person to play. Good for family, friends, and corporate events. There is also a bar in the back serving beer for those 21+ looking to wet their whistle while they wait or play. Drink holders are available at each hole for those who are still drinking their beer.

I couldn't drink while I was in SF so I can't comment on the beer selection, but from what everyone else was drinking -- it looked good.

Urban Putt is definitely a place you can bring to impress your friends or coworkers. Great way to find something new to do in the city.

5/5. Favorited in the city.< /Text>

< Text>
Loved my experience at Urban Putt! This place is a great place in the city to play indoor mini golf and also enjoy a beer or two while you're there. I love the attention to detail they have for the golf course. They have a lot of fun contraptions that the golf balls go through and I've never seen this done before. It does get pretty busy at night though, so be warned as it's a pretty small area and you'll have to wait before each hole. But overall it's still a great time if you're looking for a fun night out in the mission.</Text>

Mini golf your way through a San Francisco's neighborhood (earthquake and all!), under the sea in a submarine and through a number of fun little mazes. <rate>5</rate>< Review>
The perfect date spot!

It's often hard to find a place where you can get food, drinks, and entertainment all in one place for a great price, but Urban Putt certainly knows how to pull off this trifecta. It's a mini-golf course goldmine offering quick food service and plenty of drinks to lubricate a night of fun and enjoyment. With a 14-hole course that's steampunk themed and certainly more than just an aim-for-the-hole min-putt, you'll be delighted with a unique experience you won't find in another other city. Urban Putt delivers a high energy, unique experience that proves to be the best alternative entertainment destination for beers, birdies, brunch, and bogeys.</Review>

<UserId.>101413918357368762648<//UserId.>< user_name>
Spalding Indigo<//user_name>
< date>
1559166427514< /date>
<rating>5<//rating><Text>When I first heard of it, indoor miniature golf in San Francisco I didn't think it was gonna be great, even more so after I saw the building. It just seemed to small to be possible. Getting inside and actually giving it a go really changed my mind. It's a pretty awesome and unique experience for San Francisco. You can tell the staff who made the place put a lot of effort into every single detail. The holes each resemble some part of SF culture. As well, there's an open bar so you can drink and golf. The theme is almost steam punk in some parts and you get your golf ball out of a gumball dispenser. There's even a mini arcade and photo booth. The course is as much an art piece as it is a recreational phenomena. Also the bathrooms are ample. Kids are able to golf til 8pm so that the adults can have their peace and golf afterwards. It's a very fun course and well priced. Absolutely a must try if you're in San Francisco!< /Text>< Pictures>

A real hidden gem of a hot-spot. A true definition of "fun for all ages." This isn't your typical, hokey putt-putt place. The designers really made incredible use of the remarkably small space they have and make sure to pack in charm and engineering finesse into every inch of the establishment. < Review>
Urban Putt was easily one of the coolest experiences that was located in the tiniest place ever in one of the best districts of SF.

I came to SF with my fianc√© a few weeks ago and a bunch of our friends who live in the area took us to Urban Putt in search of a fun group activity. Although every place in SF is super tiny and cramped, this felt even more cramped especially it being a mini golf place. We came with a group of 9, and it was extremely tough especially since the holes are so close together. I guess it didn't help that we also came out on a Saturday evening. Anyways, they have a bar with beers on tap as well as light bites. There's also a room of skee ball & basketball that you have to pay $1 for. The golf experience itself was $12 per person.

The first couple of rounds were awesome as we had just started and were all super hyped up and keeping score, etc. Towards the end, our patience for each hole got less, we stopped keeping score, and skipped a few holes. It was just too crowded. Some holes were extremely difficult compared to others. For example, hole 1 was super easy, hole 2 was pretty difficult, hole 3 was hard, but hole 4 was impossible. I mean, is it not supposed to go from easy to difficult rather than jump all around? Other than a few flaws here and there, I will say that this was an amazing time. We had many laughs, some had one too many drinks, I was frustrated by the 5th hole, but all in all, I definitely recommend!</Review>

<Review>What a blast!  Started with dinner at the restaurant.  The homemade tamarind soda had just the right tartness and was not too sweet.  The dishes were flavourful and well thought out.  Friendly service and they accomodated our allergy restrictions.

The mini golf was so much fun.  It's all indoors so you don't need to worry about the weather.  The courses are all unique and the craftsmanship and planning that went into them will provide a lot of amusement.  There's just so much to take in... San Francisco icons, Rube Goldberg contraptions, and Steampunk automatons just to name a few.  My favourite was the submarine with all of the switches and sound effects.

< Review>
Being an SF Native, new businesses are often viewed with a 'side-eye' as they are too often a personification of the gentrification taking place and I tend to avoid them. However, this place was a real treat! The sculptures on the putting course were wonderful, cocktails tasty and the food was great. A fun time was had by all! It can get a bit crowded and the bulk of the clientele are not San Franciscans leading to some side-eye from them, which can get really annoying but I would definitely go back with friends. One of the only new cool spots I would recommend.<//Review>

<review>Fun and creative indoor miniature golf with a full bar and restaurant located in the SF Mission district. The golf course is 14 holes and very intimate as it's a small place. Get there early during prime times as the line for golf can get long. Takes about an hour to play with a crowded course so if you plan to have dinner in the restaurant afterwards, I highly recommend running upstairs before playing and making a reservation. The course itself has an SF feel with some cool parts that represent history like the golden fire hydrant. The restaurant serves good food at reasonable prices and the service is awesome.<//review>< Resp>

< Review>
This was my first time going to an indoor miniature golf establishment and while there were some interesting holes, the experience was not as fun for me as an outdoor miniature golf course.

Furthermore, I thought one of the perks of this place was the ability to drink alcohol while playing. Unfortunately, whether or not they allowed it in the past, we were only allowed to drink off he course, so essentially before or after playing.

Returning to the core experience, several of the holes were based more on the aesthetics or some sort of quirkiness related to the hole as opposed to the skill required to sink the ball.

Overall, there was a novelty to the experience, but it could have been better.

Note: I would consider coming back and I would consider giving the place four stars. But I don't think I'd come back any time soon; I'd sooner try and go to all the "nearby" Golflands.< /Review>
< Pictures>
None< /Pictures>
<response>{'time': 1476903725848, 'text': "Thanks for checking us out, Timothy, although it sounds like we could have made a better impression on your first visit. I would like to say that there are merits to being indoor -- this allows us to be open during all weather. In addition, our policy about drinks has always been this way, with no drinks on the course. With one MAJOR EXCEPTION: Monday. For the first day of the week, you are allowed to bring your drinks with you while you play. That said, I'm glad you noticed our focus on fun and creativity, and although it sounds like you prefer a challenge, we do hope you'll consider giving us another try. Maybe on a rainy day? -Yours in Minigolf, Steve, Chief Greenskeeper"}</response>< Gmap_id>

< Text>
Great place to play a game of mini-golf in a big, crazy city. Games are inventive and fun because the courses are so engaging/different. You can grab a drink before you play a round, though you cannot drink on the course.

Appetizers here are delicious and heart-attacking inducing. I'd suggest coming on a Monday or Tuesday because the rest of the week gets so busy/crowded that it takes away some of the fun.<//Text>

<UserId.>106289270782979631381<//UserId.>< Text>
Urban Putt is like a playground for adults! Great for a small group of friends after work or just an outing or for a date. There are 14 golf courses and each of the courses have something unique, different and beautifully designed. Alcohol on the courses are currently not allowed. They are in the process of getting a license for it. Only groups of 4 are allowed at each course. So, you + 3 of your friends would be perfect! There wouldn't be much of a long wait in line as well the wait on the course.

I suggest going there exactly at 4 pm or close to closing time which would avoid the super long lines. Word on the street is to go on the weekdays because there wouldn't be much of wait. However, when my friends and I showed up on a Thursday, there was a line wrapped around the block before the doors were open. Order drinks and wait in line. In no time, it'll be your turn. Down your drink because you won't be able to bring it on the course.< /Text>
<resp>{'time': 1414612039721, 'text': 'Hey there, Kath. I\'m glad to hear you loved the course! The word on the street is accurate -- yet, you still have to make it right around 8 to avoid the lines. There is a much shorter wait around those times, but it\'s a different crowd Monday - Wednesday. Also, we did get that special permission from the city, but when we tried out drinks on the course, it was a mess with longer waits and lots of spills. It\'s a highly debated topic among our staff, but for now, we\'re still holding up our "no drinks on the course" policy. We\'re working on ways to make this work, though! I know how fun it will be to sip and putt! Hope to see you back soon, Steve, Chief Greenskeeper'}</resp><GmapID>0x808f7e38e7b22169:0x4cdb309320bb79d< /GmapID><rate>5<//rate>< time>

So much fun! It's a 13 hole SF Themed miniature golf complex that you can get through within an hour.  The best time to go is during the week in the evenings.  Don't bother trying to go during the weekend as the lines are long.  They also have full bar and delicious appetizers.  Get the Chicken and Waffle skewers and deviled eggs.

<userid>113642846829972362290<//userid>< name>
Taylor Reding</name>
<date>1554958848518</date>< Rate>
4</Rate>
<Review>Food was really good and the course was fun. My only complaint is that the space is pretty small and the holes can be really really long in terms of the time it takes to complete them. There are at least 4 holes with tube goldberg-like contraptions that last at least a minute and if the place is packed it can really add up, not to mention my ball disappeared inside two of them(the broken windmill and the gold rush holes).

My wife and I spent over 10 minutes on two occassions waiting between holes cause the parties(4 and 3 people) ahead of us played the hole like it was supposed to be played. This is mini golf not real golf, people shouldn't feel pressured to let others play ahead or play faster just because the course literally requires you to watch your ball traverse a half mile of track just for you to tap it in when it's done.

With drinks and a packed house be prepared to get hot. There isn't a lot of room between holes and the back area can get very crowded.

Overall I enjoyed it and if I went again it would be when it's significantly less busy.<//Review><pictures>None<//pictures>< Response>

< Text>
I would've given 5 stars if it weren't for 2 reasons: the place was crowded with no time slots so you end waiting for a bit until someone finishes the hole and second reason being I haven't tried their bar yet. An excellent place to spend time with friends or a date. Looks more like a Maker style venue. The contraptions and holes are well thought out and a lot of fun. The most interesting of all is probably the labyrinth. There are some tricky ones too but all fun though. Go ahead and grab a few friends or your date and head on over there for a fun evening trying to sink the golf ball hitting par while navigating the SF scenery in miniature mode.< /Text>

< Review>
12 dollars will get you a very unique SF experience. We arrived on a Saturday night around 9 and we were told there was "a line for the line" and it would take about an hour. The 40 minutes that it took to get on the course flew by as we sipped on some dogfish head from the bar and played a really cool game in line (you'll see). Go with a group of friends or a date; it's only 4 per hole at a time, but if you go when it's busy it'll be a line of people moving through anyway. Worth the wait if you've never done it, I'll be bringing some other first timers here in the future.<//Review>

<date>1539289994066</date><user_id>101713808907494473443<//user_id></record></dataset><record>
<userid>111414489430298948350</userid><Name>Tu Lam< /Name><Time>1429598201445< /Time><rate>4</rate>< Text>
I grew up playing lots of miniature golf.  In college we use to buy best player dinner.  Now this is a great twist to the game.  Indoor gold with food and drinks.  Note you can't bring food or drinks onto the course.

There's a total of 14 holes, each one with their own theme, but many related to the bay area.  Some courses have a tricky shot, but you can always take the long way around the obstacle, but if you get pass, you can cut your strokes down.

They also have rooms for private events and a restaurant upstairs.  It gets crazy busy at 7:30ish.  A line forms for just by the bar to get on the course.  If you can, try to start your game by 7:00.</Text>
< pics>
None< /pics>

<Resp>{'time': 1529360134284, 'text': "You rock! Thanks for stopping by -- can't wait 'til next time! -Yours in Minigolf, Steve, Chief Greenskeeper"}<//Resp>< gmap_id>
0x808f7e38e7b22169:0x4cdb309320bb79d</gmap_id>
<time>1529166316616</time>< user>
108852369590640468620< /user>
</record>
</dataset><record>
< Review>
I chose this place to meet with my friends for my birthday because I've heard good things and it was only $12 per person.  Every employee I ran into was friendly and helpful, from the women checking IDs at the door to the woman handling the transactions.

The putting area was so much fun!  Each hole has a unique San Francisco theme.  I'm not going to spoil the surprise by describing each one.  And Googling pictures won't help you.  You just have to see them for yourself!

The only criticism I have is crowd control.  The bar is across the entrance to the putting area, so it gets confusing.  I didn't know which line to stand in as they started to converge.  Also, there is seating area to the side of the putting area if you want to drink and observe.  But if you're sitting there and the line gets longer, you end up with people trying to maneuver behind you and it can get frustrating.  Also, there's no more than 4 people per hole, so if a golfer's game isn't up to par, or if there's a large group of people ahead, it can get backed up.  I'm not sure what the solution would be, because I also don't think people should feel rushed.

So if you're planning on going on a Friday or Saturday night, just be prepared with a lot of patience.

And before you leave, check out the art installation by the golf clubs.  It's interactive and must be done a couple of times just because!< /Review>

<review>Mortuary converted into a unique mini golf course. Not your standard, suburban course, it's very compact, features incredibly detailed construction, Rube Goldberg machines for transporting balls, and a ball race. < name>
Lu Rosebrook</name>
< Text>
Coming into Urban Putt, you can tell that they put a lot of thought and details into the design of the place. I haven't been upstairs, but I think that area is for dining. But downstairs is where all the action is at. They have a room with some mini games, a photo booth, but the money is on the mini golf course/bar.

We had to wait in line, to get into a line! Haha, that sounds ridiculous right? On a Saturday, we waited around 1 hour for a party of 3. I wish that the place was slightly bigger, I was often bumping into people, but that's not really a big deal. Urban Putt is a really fun place to be, you can bring a date, people from out of town or whatever - you won't be disappointed :-)

P.S. They use banana chips for their guacamole dip so don't miss out on that!<//Text>

<UserId.>107451670322805881138</UserId.><Name>Jeff Frank< /Name><time>1519947784214</time><Rate>5< /Rate><review>More whimsy per sq inch than anywhere else in SF!

If this indoor putt-putt‚Äã golf course were a math equation it would be Rube Goldberg x Willy Wonka + Exploratorium  Disney √∑ Steampunk  Guillermo Del Toro = Urban Putt.

Yes, it gets very crowded & you may have to wait to tee off BUT fear not adults as they feature an expertly crafted full bar with a cocktail menu (plus beer & wine) to match the equally creative course. Oh and they do have some damn tasty vittles to keep your backswing fully powered Tiger (bar bites to full entrees).

Also great for kids...but super duper crowded in a very tight space so parents beware.

Open @ 4pm weekdays & 11am weekend.

Admission:
Kids under 5 = free
6-12 = $8
13 & Up = $12

They host tons of private events & parties so best to check before you get your knickers & argyle on.

<userid>118246307859485381903<//userid>< user_name>
Michael Hraba</user_name>
<Date>1401420550399</Date><Rate>5<//Rate>< Text>
5 Stars because of me being a cynic. This is downstairs bar and golf, no upstairs info from my end....

Gastropub comfort food that will eventually kill you, but for the night it was delightful. Corn Dogs, Soft Pretzels, Deep Dish Pizza (this was meh, fine, okay, but don't come looking for solid DD). Mostly expect deep fried things.

As a boozer, I get irate with wine and beer only places, so 5 stars in lieu of that is a happy recommendation.  They always have lovely sparkling bubbles.

No booze allowed on the course yet due to awesomely complex and obscure permitting issues, but it did seem a beer or two snuck their way on the course from time to time.  The food felt like I was at a fair - delicious gut bombs that you pay for, later.

But the course is really special. I thought it would be a stupid hipster event that was awful. And yes... the line and wait is awful. But the course itself is sheer brilliance... 14 creative and artistic holes in a tiny space, that were designed with an obviously non-ironic and profound sense of love, experimentation, and fun.  This was not dialed in, phoned in, or any of that. It is a cute, engaging, enjoyable, imaginative and fun time in SF.

Enjoy.<//Text>

<Name>Chase Kelley<//Name>< time>
1512939130388< /time>
<Rating>4< /Rating><text>Ah, Urban Putt. A sanctuary for playing your favorite childhood activity and an adult, where you an scarf down some grub and embellish yourself with one of many classy cocktails or humble beers on the drink menu. Don't be off-put by the long lines seen from the door, as the slight intimidation of the Door Guard will dissipate as you hear him chuckle about the shenanigans he sees on a friday night.

I ventured in here for a work event and brought my beautiful fiance. Our doggy Charlie stayed home as all the hussle and bussle of this lively happenin' place would frighten the little pup.

The lines move quick. We played some Ski-Ball before our tournament and choose one of the wild neon colored balls. A bit of foreshadowing, because to our pleasant surprise, they actually glowed in the dark! Just a little hint for you curious guides!

There is a chart to choose the correct club length! Make sure you do this or else all your friends will laugh as you crouch over a stick that is way too short! Just a heads up as my fiance chose a stick that was too long and we traded.

The mini golf holes inside this wonderful nostalgic victorian home are just as creative as the place itself. Mini scenes from San Fran adorn all of the course and leave you mesmerized with Rube Goldberg type devices. We won't spoil it for you as this place is a MUST visit.

The lines move quick. Everyone is pretty respectful, and our only complaint comes from the crowd of slightly-too-buzzed tech workers that kept hitting their ball into other courses and ruining our game. It would have been forgivable if they didn't further this behavior in other places like loud drunken chats in the bathroom and halls. My fiance didn't really approve of her experience with a few patrons, but don't be alarmed - Urban Putt lives up to all the hype!

Next time we go when my fiance's sister is in town we will definitely go when Google says it isnt too busy and show her a little Frisco fun!

Urban Putt is a creative, adult playground with all you could want. Make sure you go when it is slow. Thanks, good peoples!<//text><Pics>None</Pics>< Resp>

<resp>{'time': 1423529532282, 'text': "Hahah thanks, Jennifer. I'm loving this review and the puns, of course!  Thanks for thinking to leave us this great review -- it's really too sweet. Hope to see you back soon for more putting and boozing! Yours in Minigolf, Steve, Chief Greenskeeper"}<//resp><text>This place just screams date night to me or fun group outing!

In my case it was a fun group outing. My friends and I were around the area and couldn't help but stop by to check this place out. It's a mini golf, restaurant, and bar all in one! You can eat, grab some drinks, and mini golf all under one roof! How awesome is that?!

It gets pretty packed but the place is pretty big. The second level is the restaurant, and the first level is the mini golf area. Both levels have a bar but the one on the first level is bigger and has more drink selections (beers on tap). The mini golf area contains 14 holes all jammed up on the first floor. They get pretty creative with the hole designs since space is limited and it was fun to go through all of them. They get major props for decorations and everything! It costs about $12 dollars to play which isn't bad. There isn't any drinking allowed during golfing so drink up before or afterwards. The line can get pretty backed up for the holes since a lot of people play but it's still fun. The crowd is pretty lively and cheerful.

It was a fun experience and I wouldn't mind going back. The convenience is really what gets me, you don't have to leave to get a drink or food :D Definitely something you should check out if you're ever in the area and looking to have a swingin' night ;) ( I just can't help being punny )<//text>< user_name>

<user_id>105807229645565556712< /user_id><Name>Ben Mo<//Name>< date>
1495588068797<//date>
<rate>5< /rate>< text>
One of the best, compact miniature golf courses you'll ever play. Top-notch design elements and theming. Lots of rube golderg type contraptions on the back-half of course to extend gameplay - feels gimmicky sometimes but is genuinely entertaining overall.

As an added bonus, you can take your drink on the course now.

Bar has ready-to-serve margheritas and good beer/cocktail selection. The food is way above average - highly recommend the chicken-and-waffles and grilled cheese w/ tomato soup. To top it all off, they have Straus soft-serve for dessert.<//text>

<userid>109990015325101967520<//userid>< review>
Pretty neat place! Too bad you can't bring your beverages inside the minigolf course, so, I suggest you drink enough to get a good buzz and play minigolf! Each hole is unique and my friend and I were snapping pictures left and right. My favorite was hole 9, Dia de los muertos. When you come, you'll find out why. I definitely think you should check it out. It's super cool and fun! Urban Putt also has a mini arcade with mini hoops, skeeball and a few others. In my opinion, those games are the best!

Lastly, the beer menu ranges from light to dark with various beers on tap. The bar menu wasn't extensive and we ordered fried green olives with goat cheese and jalapenos. The burger looked good and we saw many others order it too.

I'd come back again and a neat place for everyone of all ages!<//review>

<Text>I went here for a first date and it is perfect for that - provides a fun experience that you can enjoy so you don't spend the whole time trying to think what to say.

Plusses:
- The course is really creative and uses scenes from around San Francisco (including little buildings that shake as though there is an earthquake, and a pretty cool Dia de Los Muertos display)
- It's not too crowded even though it's a putt putt course in a bar
- It's clean and well kept up
- It's a fun, young crowd for the most part (some families but not after 8pm)
- They've been creative about drinks despite lacking their liquor license - lots of fun beer/wine based choices that are pretty good
- There is Skeeball in the back room
- The holes are challenging but not so much that you can't move through pretty quickly

Minuses:
- The line will be long. Just have to deal with it
- They lack their liquor license (at the moment)
- The food, which I did not try, looked iffy. Like pizza was largely a slab of cheese melted on top of a hunk of bread. Truly gross looking - again, I didn't taste it, but didn't seem like what you wanted, and it's unfortunate as they're in a neighborhood where you expect good food.
-<//Text>< UserId.>
